{{Chembox | ImageFile = Levoglucosan.png | ImageFile_Ref = {{chemboximage|correct|??}} | ImageSize = 121 | ImageName = Stereo skeletal formula of levoglucosan | IUPACName = (1''R'',2''S'',3''S'',4''R'',5''R'')-6,8-Dioxabicyclo[3.2.1]octane-2,3,4-triol | OtherNames = 1,6-Anhydro-''beta''-glucopyranose Leucoglucosan |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo = 498-07-7 | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}} | PubChem = 2724705 | ChemSpiderID = 9587432 | ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{Chemspidercite|correct|ChemSpider}} | EINECS = 207-855-0 | MeSHName = 1,6-Anhydro-beta-glucopyranose | ChEBI = 30997 | Beilstein = 80998 | SMILES = OC1C2COC(O2)C(O)C1O | StdInChI = 1S/C6H10O5/c7-3-2-1-10-6(11-2)5(9)4(3)8/h2-9H,1H2 | StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}} | StdInChIKey = TWNIBLMWSKIRAT-UHFFFAOYSA-N | StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}} }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | C=6 | H=10 | O=5 | Appearance = Colorless crystals | Density = 1.688 g·cm<sup>−3</sup> (predicted) | MeltingPtC = 182 to 184 | BoilingPtC = 384 | BoilingPt_notes = predicted | LogP = -0.04 (predicted) | VaporPressure = 24.1 μPa (predicted) }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | FlashPtC = 185.9 | FlashPt_notes = (predicted) }} }}
'''Levoglucosan''' (C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>10</sub>O<sub>5</sub>) is an [[organic compound]] with a six-[[carbon]] ring structure formed from the [[pyrolysis]] of carbohydrates, such as [[starch]] and [[cellulose]].<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/i360033a011 | title = Production of Levoglucosan by Pyrolysis of Carbohydrates. Pyrolysis in Hot Inert Gas Stream | year = 1970 | last1 = Lakshmanan | first1 = Chambra M. | last2 = Hoelscher | first2 = Harold E. | journal = Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Product Research and Development | volume = 9 | pages = 57–59}}</ref> As a result, levoglucosan is often used as a chemical tracer for [[biomass]] burning in atmospheric chemistry studies, particularly with respect to [[Atmospheric particulate matter|airborne particulate matter]]. Along with other tracers such as potassium, oxalate, and gaseous acetonitrile,<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.5194/acp-10-5315-2010 | title = Mexico city aerosol analysis during MILAGRO using high resolution aerosol mass spectrometry at the urban supersite (T0) – Part 2: Analysis of the biomass burning contribution and the non-fossil carbon fraction | year = 2010 | last1 = Aiken | first1 = A. C. | last2 = De Foy | first2 = B. | last3 = Wiedinmyer | first3 = C. | last4 = Decarlo | first4 = P. F. | last5 = Ulbrich | first5 = I. M. | last6 = Wehrli | first6 = M. N. | last7 = Szidat | first7 = S. | last8 = Prevot | first8 = A. S. H. | last9 = Noda | first9 = J. | last10 = Wacker | first10 = L. | last11 = Volkamer | first11 = R. | last12 = Fortner | first12 = E. | last13 = Wang | first13 = J. | last14 = Laskin | first14 = A. | last15 = Shutthanandan | first15 = V. | last16 = Zheng | first16 = J. | last17 = Zhang | first17 = R. | last18 = Paredes-Miranda | first18 = G. | last19 = Arnott | first19 = W. P. | last20 = Molina | first20 = L. T. | last21 = Sosa | first21 = G. | last22 = Querol | first22 = X. | last23 = Jimenez | first23 = J. L. | journal = Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics | volume = 10 | issue = 12 | pages = 5315| display-authors = 8 }}</ref> levoglucosan has been shown to be highly correlated with regional fires. This is because the gas emitted by the pyrolysis of wood (biomass) contains significant amounts of levoglucosan.
Levoglucosan has been described as "an unequivocal biomass burning tracer" in the context of forest and brush fires.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Identification of biomass burning tracers|journal=Euro 'Milestone' Survey|url=http://airuse.eu/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/B4-2MILESTONE-tracers-biomass.pdf|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref> But the anhydrosugar has only been found detectable in low temperature samples (150-350&nbsp;°C), meaning that its value as an indicator for smoke from controlled biomass combustion in, for instance, modern domestic wood stoves which operate at temperatures above 500&nbsp;°C, is "very doubtful".<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.atmosenv.2013.08.026| title = An evaluation of some issues regarding the use of aethalometers to measure woodsmoke concentrations| journal = Atmospheric Environment| volume = 80| pages = 540–548| year = 2013| last1 = Harrison| first1 = Roy M.| last2 = Beddows| first2 = David C.S.| last3 = Jones| first3 = Alan M.| last4 = Calvo| first4 = Ana| last5 = Alves| first5 = Célia| last6 = Pio| first6 = Casimiro}}</ref> Levoglucosan is a marker for coal combustion as well as wood.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/acs.est.7b05858 | pmid = 29244948 | title = Residential Coal Combustion as a Source of Levoglucosan in China | journal = Environmental Science & Technology | volume = 52 | issue = 3 | pages = 1665–1674 | year = 2018 | last1 = Yan | first1 = Caiqing | last2 = Zheng | first2 = Mei | last3 = Sullivan | first3 = Amy P. | last4 = Shen | first4 = Guofeng | last5 = Chen | first5 = Yingjun | last6 = Wang | first6 = Shuxiao | last7 = Zhao | first7 = Bin | last8 = Cai | first8 = Siyi | last9 = Desyaterik | first9 = Yury | last10 = Li | first10 = Xiaoying | last11 = Zhou | first11 = Tian | last12 = Gustafsson | first12 = Örjan | last13 = Collett | first13 = Jeffrey L. }}</ref>
The hydrolysis of levoglucosan generates the fermentable sugar [[glucose]]. Levoglucosan can be utilized in the synthesis of chiral polymers such as [[unhydrolysable glucose polymers]].
==References== {{Reflist}}
